.CE
.CS "Redistribution of Materials"
.PP
The best way to maintain economic stability within a nation is to make
sure that each supply center has some of each of the four production
type sectors within its range of influence.  There are times, however,
when this is not possible, such as when first establishing a new
supply center.  In such cases, it is often necessary to move materials
into the supply center from other supply centers in the area.
.PP
There are two ways to move materials into a supply center:  transfer
them directly from a nearby supply center or place them in a caravan
or navy and carry them there.
.PP
Transferring directly between supply centers is done using the
"region-command" function.  The maximum distance over which this is
possible is determined by the campaign administrator, but by default
is two sectors.  Placing a number of supply centers within range of
each other makes it possible to "string" supplies over long distances
from one supply center to another for free.  The problem with this
approach is that supplies may not be moved over more than one supply
center per month, so it might take a long time to get supplies to or
from cities farther out in the nation.
.PP
Transporting materials over land or water using caravans or navies
provides the quickest method of transfer, as long distances may
sometimes be covered over a single turn.  However, this method
requires materials to build the units, and civilians to crew the
transports.  Once a supply network of caravans and navies is in place,
though, the support costs are rather low and the speed of material
relocation is worth the added expenses.  Loading and unloading of
materials from caravans and navies is accomplished using the
"transfer" command or the (T)fer Cargo option of the "command-unit"
function.
.CE
.CS "The xfer screen"
.PP
The "xfer" screen used by both the "transfer" and "region-command"
functions is a simple multi-column display with one storage site on
the left and another on the right.  Using the "hjkl" keys items are
transferred between the two locations, and until the screen is quit,
items may be freely moved between the two sites.
.PP
Only those materials which may be transferred between the two storage
sites will be shown on the screen.  So army units will not be shown
unless the transfer is between a naval fleet with warships and a
sector with units or another warship fleet.  Also, once raw materials
are placed in a supply center, they are not able to be transferred
again until the next month.  This mechanism prevents "instant"
transfer of materials between supply centers from one end of a nation
to another.
.PP
The transfer screen shows the capacities for each storage location and
the current amounts in that location.  Each line also contains a
"default transfer amount" which will be used to transfer materials if
only a portion of the materials needs to be transferred.
.CE
.CS "Commands for the xfer Screen"
.PP
The list of commands available during the "xfer" screen:
.IT
conquer-options (`O') -- Adjust environment by changing various
options, including keybindings.
.IT
redraw-screen (`^L',`^R') -- Redraw the display of the screen.
.IT
xfer-add (`+') -- Increase the current default transfer amount by one.
.IT
xfer-assign (`=') -- Assign a value the the default transfer amount.
.IT
xfer-divide (`/') -- Divide the default transfer amount by ten.
.IT
xfer-down (`J',`j',`^N',DOWN-ARROW) -- Move the selection pointer down
one line.
.IT
xfer-help (`?') -- Provide a listing of functions and key bindings.
.IT
xfer-left (`H',`h',`<'`^B',LEFT-ARROW) -- Change transfer direction
from left-to-right to right-to-left, or if already done, move as much
as possible from the right to the left.
.IT
xfer-move (` ') -- Transfer the current default amount in the current
direction.
.IT
xfer-multiply (`*') -- Multiply the default transfer amount by ten.
.IT
xfer-quit (`Q',`q') -- Exit the transfer mode, finalizing transfers.
.IT
xfer-right (`L',`l',`>',`^F',RIGHT-ARROW) -- Change transfer direction
from right-to-left to left-to-right, or if already done, move as much
as possible from the left to the right.
.IT
xfer-shiftdown (`p') -- Move the list of army or caravan units downward.
.IT
xfer-shiftup (`o') -- Move the list of army or caravan units upward.
.IT
xfer-subtract (`-') -- Decrease the default transfer amount by one.
.IT
xfer-up (`K',`k',`^P',UP-ARROW) -- Move the selection pointer upward
one line.
.UT
.CE
.CS "The National Information Screen"
.PP
The "nation-information" function is a good way of gathering a summary
of your national status.  It includes information about many national
statistics and traits, and examining it every turn and noting trends
is a good way to chart national progress.  When using the function,
the display will be similar to this:
.SB
