 NPC status......NPC Mine Ability.LowAvg                     Leaders.........19
                     Morale..........Low                     Soldiers......2019
 Tax Rate.........10 Popularity...VryLow                     Civilians....64824
 Charity...........0 Reputation...VryLow                     Monsters.........0
 Currency........Avg Spell Pts.........0                     Ship Holds.......0
 Inflation.........0 Spoilrate........90                     Wagons...........0
                     Terror.......VryLow                     Sectors.........14
                     Wizardcraft.....Min                     Score...........53
.SE
.PP
The above screen shows an NPC Dwarven nation named Khazadum with a
ruler named Durin.  Whenever other nations encounter Khazadum, they
will see a 'k' on their maps, since that is its nation mark.  The
aggressiveness of the nation indicates that its troops will be mostly
defensive, and within their fortifications.  The tax rate is moderate,
with inflation and currency levels stable.
.PP
The eat rate is at a good low level, but the communication range is
a little low for a nation of this size.  The metal craft and mine
ability are very low and there is no magical power potential within
the nation.  Those are probably due to the nation not having either
shrines within magical sectors or metal mines.  Given the lack of wood
as well, it is possible that there are also no lumberyards within the
nation.  The last two items are potentially crippling.
.PP
On the whole, the nation seems to be in a bit of trouble, with most of
the attributes being very low to average, and the metal and wood
supplies having run out.  It will take a fair amount of work to get
this nation out of trouble, particularly in regard to the wood and
metal levels.
.CE
.CS "National Attributes"
.PP
The nation information screen is used to display a number of the
attributes of a nation.  Items marked with an asterisk (*) have the
possible values: Min, VryLow, Low, LowAvg, Avg, HghAvg, High, VryHgh,
and Max.  Those marked with a plus (+) are adjustable by the user.
.IT
Nation+ -- The name of the nation, which may be changed at any time.
.IT
Nation Mark+ -- What map character is used to represent the nation.
.IT
Leader+ -- The name of the ruler of the nation.
.IT
Race -- The race of the nation.
.RF "Nations" "Racial Traits and Nation Roles"
.IT
Alignment -- The general moralistic leaning of the nation.  The
possible alignments are: Good, Neutral, Evil, or Other.  Only the
first three are available to active nations.
.IT
Class -- The national class.
.RF "Nations" "Racial Traits and Nation Roles"
.IT
Aggression+ -- This indicates the type of update a computer player
will make for the nation, if a computer update is made.  Computer
aggressiveness ranges from Static to Killer and can be turned off with
the value Nomove.
.IT
NPC Status+ -- Is the nation controlled by a player or by the
computer?  If controlled by the computer, the status is NPC.
.IT
Tax Rate+ -- What level of taxes are drawn from the civilians.  This
may range between 0 and 25, but the higher the setting, the lower the
popularity of the government.
.IT
Charity+ -- How much of the yearly treasury is distributed back to the
civilian population each year.  The more that is given, the higher the
popularity of the government.
.IT
Currency* -- The strength of the national currency.
.IT
Inflation -- The yearly inflation, or deflation if negative, of the
national currency.
.IT
Communication -- The distance over which communication is possible.
This rate is a factor of the density of supply centers within a
nation, and the availability of roads for transportation of messages.
.IT
Eat Rate -- An indication of how much food per month civilians will
each.  The amount of food within the nation and the time of year will
determine how much high this value is.
.IT
Health* -- The average overall national health of the civilian
population.  If this attribute is low, the population will be more
susceptible to disease and famine.  Having civilians who are not
properly supplied will lower the national health rate.
.IT
Jewelcraft* -- An indicator of how adept the nation is add taking raw
gems and turning them into jewelry.  The better the jewelcraft, the
greater the national skill in locating additional jewel deposits.
.IT
Knowledge* -- A measurement of the technological level of the nation.
The greater the knowledge, the easier it is to accure new magical
powers.
.IT
Merc Rep* -- An indicator of the respect shown to the nation by
mercenary organizations around the world.  Higher respect means lower
enlistment and support costs for mercenary troops.
.IT
Metalcraft* -- Akin to Jewelcraft for metal minerals, a higher value
means that locating new metal deposites will be easier.
.IT
Mine Ability* -- A measurement of the ability of the nation to remove
minerals from mines.  A higher value indicates an easier time in
locating new mineral deposits.
.IT
Morale* -- The general confidence of the national military.  A lower
morale means a higher chance of desertion for soldiers.
.IT
Popularity* -- An indicator of how well-liked the government is by its
civilian population.  A higher popularity means a lower likelyhood for
rebellion.
.IT
Reputation* -- A measurement of how well regarded the nation is by
other nations in the world.  A higher reputation will mean better
deals when trading with other nations.
.IT
Spell Pts -- A numerical indicator for how much magical ability is
within the nation.  This number dictates the maximum magical potential
of the national leaders and spellcasters.
.IT
Spoilrate -- An indicator of how quickly food will spoil within the
nation.  The percentage value is a measurement for how much of the
current supply will be decayed within the nation over a year.
.IT
Terror* -- How much fear for the national government does the civilian
population feel.  A higher fear rate indicates a lesser likelyhood of
rebellion.
.IT
Wizardcraft* -- A measurement of how adept the nation is at magical
tasks.  The higher the wizardcraft, the higher the success in spell
casting.
.IT
Attack Bonus -- This number is added directly to the combat value of
any of this nation's military units during an attack.
.RF "Warfare" "Miltary Units and Combat"
.IT
Defense Bonus -- This number is added directly to the combat value of
any of this nation's military units during any other combat situation.
.RF "Warfare" "Miltary Units and Combat"
.IT
Reproduction -- This percentage represents what level of growth the
national civilian population will experience each year.  Of course,
this is compounded monthly, so returns on investments may vary.
.IT
Movement -- A numerical measurement of the national movement
potential.  This is a reflection of both physical prowess of the
soldiers and of the ability of the military to relay orders.
.RF "Movement" "Unit Relocation"
.IT
Score -- A numerical measure of how many resources a nation has.
Factors in determining the score include: amount of land owned, size
of the military and civilian populations, and the amount of raw
materials produced and stored in supply centers.
.UT
.PP
The items in the last column are simple measurements of various
quantities within the nation such as the raw materials and military
units.
.CE
.CS "The nation-information Functions"
.PP
A summary of those functions available in the nation information
screen:
.IT
conquer-options (`O',`o') -- Adjust the conquer environment by
changing various options.
.IT
ignore-key (`^@') -- Don't do anything when this keybinding is
pressed.
.IT
info-backward (`^H',`^?') -- Move backward among the list of items on
the information screen.
.IT
info-change (ESC,`C',`c') -- If allowed, change the value of the
currently selected item.
.IT
info-change-backward (`B',`b') -- If allowed, change the current item,
by decreasing the value, if applicable.
.IT
info-change-forward (`N',`n') -- If permissible, change the current
item, by increasing the value, if applicable.
.IT
info-description (`I',`i') -- Provide a description of the current
item.
.IT
info-destroy (`D',`d') -- God may remove the nation using this
command.
.IT
info-down (`^N',DOWN-ARROW,`J',`j') -- Move down along the list of
items on the screen.
.IT
info-exit (`Q',`q') -- Leave the national information screen.
.IT
info-forward (`^I',`^J',`^M',` ') -- Move forward among the list of
items on the screen.
.IT
info-help (`?') -- List all of the commands and bindings in this mode.
.IT
info-left (`^B',LEFT-ARROW,`H',`h') -- Move to the item to the left of
the current item.
.IT
info-passwd (`X',`x') -- Change the national password using this
command.
.IT
info-reset (`R',`r') -- Reset the national attributes back to the
settings they had upon entering the screen.
.IT
info-right (`^F',RIGHT-ARROW,`L',`l') -- Move to the item to the right
of the current item.
.IT
info-up (`^P',UP-ARROW,`K',`k') -- Move upwards along the list of
items on the screen.
.IT
redraw-screen (`^L',`^R') -- Redraw the screen without clearing it
first.
.UT
.CE
